<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-09-30T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-09-30T09:00:00-05:00" n="979" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d979">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/15491:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-09-30T16:00:00+02:00">September 30, 1941—4
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 5:16 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>364. I have several times reported the belief of Turkish officials
                                that Turkey need fear no attack by Germany at any rate until spring.
                                This has now developed into a conviction (which within the past few
                                days both Foreign Minister and Secretary General have <pb facs="0912" n="904" xml:id="pg_904"/> stated categorically to
                                British Ambassador, and leading staff officers to our Military
                                Attaché) that such an attack is to be definitely expected next
                                spring.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>